  "texts": [
    "Proof: We first prove the claim about S p C. For any R > 0, denote by C(R) the subregion of C consisting of all vertices, edges and faces of C that are contained inB R = {v ∈ R 2: ∥v∥ ∞ ≤ R}.There is an R 0 such that for all R ≥ R 0 large enough, the associated surface Σ C(R) is homeomorphic to an annulus.",
    "The inner boundary component of Σ C(R) is the same as the unique boundary component of Σ C, and so comes with the same Tube S representation t. Let S R be the outer boundary component of Σ C(R) and denote by t R = t S R the Tube S R action associated to that boundary component.Since p is minimal, it has definite type X for some X ∈ Irr Z(C).",
    "By Theorem 4.7 there is a unique density matrix inD C(R) (p, ⋆ X) defining a state ψ R on A C(R) for all R ≥ R 0.",
    "By Theorem 4.9, ψ R ′ | C(R) = ψ R whenever R ′ > R, so it is clear that ψ(O) = lim R↑∞ ψ R (O) defines a state on A locC which extends uniquely to a state ψ: A C → C. By construction ψ R (t(p)) = 1 for all R > R 0, and ψ R (B f) = 1 for f ∈ F C whenever R is large enough, so ψ ∈ S p C. To see that ψ is the only state in S p C it suffices to note that the restriction of any state in S p C to the region C(R) for R ≥ R 0 corresponds to the unique density matrix in D C(R) (p, ⋆ X).To see that ψ is pure, suppose ψ = λψ 1 + (1 -λ)ψ 2 for some λ ∈ (0, 1).",
    "For any projector q, if ψ(q) = 1 then λψ 1 (q) + (1 -λ)ψ 2 (q) = 1, which can only hold if ψ 1 (q) = ψ 2 (q) = 1."
  ],
